Happy Easter, everyone! The Easter Bunny brought us a special little something this year. 

After three IUIs and three IVF egg retrievals we decided to transfer one of our embryos. 

Little embryo 6BB has started to grow into our little fella.

Finished copies of my new book have arrived! 🥰 I’m so excited for you to read it when it comes out in June.

In addition to sharing strategies in the book for how women can incorporate intermittent fasting to reach their health goals, I also share my own story: in my 20s, I struggled with PCOS, non-alcoholic fatty liver disease, and was diagnosed with type 2 diabetes. After hearing about intermittent fasting at the clinic where I was a researcher, I was able to reverse these conditions and lose over 80 pounds. Now, I help women from all stages of life take control of their health. This book is informed by their experiences, and even features some of their stories. ❤️

You can preorder it through the link in my bio.

👉Megan Ramos returns to the Keto Kamp Podcast for a brand new episode all about her new book. 

You may have heard that fasting for women is different than it is for men but do you know why? Today, Megan Ramos educates us on the intricacies of fasting for women of all ages and across all life stages. Whether you’re cycling, going through menopause or postmenopausal, this video will explain why fasting must complement hormones, and how this affects energy, food cravings and more. We’ll also discuss the art of eating, finding a balance between data and intuition, the debilitating effects of environmental toxins (such as mold), as well as how PCOS can cause infertility or simply, make pregnancy far more challenging for some women.🔝

Get Megan’s New Book “The Essential Guide to Intermittent Fasting for Women” today!🙌

✅️In this clip, Megan shares her recent challenges with mold toxicity. Listen to the full interview on The Keto Kamp Podcast, episode 599. (link in bio)
Baby Marcus is a few days ahead of schedule and growing very well!

Bela has an incredible interview with one of her personal heroes, Megan Ramos, best-selling author of “The Essential Guide to Intermittent Fasting for Women.” Megan and her business partner, Dr. Jason Fung, are some of the most renowned researchers in health and fasting. Intermittent fasting is something that can benefit so many of us, and the benefits are massive overall. Listen to Megan drop her best gems including: 

How we have been sold a ‘bill of goods’ about what & when we should eat 
How the average American woman has tried 126 diets by the age of 50 
How Megan hired Canada’s most expensive nutritionist and trainer, and ended up gaining over 80 lbs (and developing Type 2 Diabetes at 27) 
Why have we become ‘unhealthier’ as the decades have gone on 
How to fix things for good, and it requires NO money, special foods, etc. 
Bela loves Megan (and Dr. Fung) and learned of their work on a girls’ weekend in 2021. Her life and health have changed for the better since then, and we hope you will find this episode incredibly enlightening!

The universe has decided that Mr. Marcus will be a pumpkin rather than a turkey.  We’re staying put at the hospital for a few days before he joins the party.  Both mom and baby are doing well. The little guy will be full-term upon his arrival. 

Dad is busy trying to find a newborn sized Mandalorian outfit for Halloween now that Marcus will be on the outside lol. 

For TFM related matters, my awesome team will in touch early next week with updates. 

We will share an update once everything settles on our end.

Marcus Alexander Ramos entered the world on October 24th, 2023 a bit ahead of schedule. He weighed in at 5 lbs, 8 oz and 18 inches long. 

Baby, mom and dad are all doing well! 

We’ve had a long day but will share some more pictures and updates tomorrow.

Bath time! 🛁 

He may be a bit of a premie because of his goofy placenta  but he’s doing very well ❤️

A week ago today we were diagnosed with vasa previa. When this rare placenta complication occurs, the baby needs to be born via c-section before 37 weeks.  Since Marcus was measuring a tiny bit on the smaller side, our doctor hoped that a week of bed rest in the hospital with monitoring would allow him to get to full-term. I was scheduled for a c-section today at noon. 

In the early hours of Tuesday morning, I had a couple of mild contractions. That was enough of a risk for my care team to move everything up. Before I knew it, Mr. Marcus was with us by 9:10 AM. 

He weighed 5lbs, 8oz upon his arrival. All babies will lose weight during the first little bit, but we didn’t have much to wiggle room with his lower birthweight.  He dropped to 4lbs, 15 oz. 

He was (and still is) taking my colostrum like a complete champ, but we had to start to supplement with donor breast milk. I’ll forever be grateful for the mommas out there who donate their excess supply while mine begins to kick in. 

Yesterday, between breastfeeding and the donor milk, Mr. Marcus was able to sustain his weight!  My milk is coming in  now, too, and he’s doing well latching. 

We also had a big day of tests and assessments yesterday and our first bath.  It looks like we’ll be going home tomorrow.  We’re very fortunate to have some good resources at home to help us adapt. 

The c-section wasn’t a part of the birth plan and recovery isn’t a walk in the park, but we’re happy and healthy, which is all that matters in the end.

Thank you to everyone who has reached out. It’s been hard to respond to everyone since all I do right now is feed, feed, feed (lol), but we really do appreciate your kind notes and well wishes ❤️
Homeward bound to meet his puppy doggos! 🏡 🐶 🐶 👶
Happy Halloween 🎃 👻
